These steps are the mustard seed of Faith God wants to see from us. He won't reveal himself until you do them guininly. Don't believe me, nor anyone else, do these steps and get the Truth for yourself. I can say with absolute certainly that they work 100% of the time. You just have to be guinine, it's not hard, you will know if you're not, and so will God. If you're seriously interested in the Truth, this is the pathway to it. There's actually very important reasons everything is set up this way, and why Faith is key. God will inform you directly after you do these steps, explaining everything you need to know personally. Very serious here. An actual one on one conversation. Not feelings, not signs, not anything you're going to misinterpret. An extremely real event. You see, Faith is important because it's something we can all find inside of ourselves. It doesn't matter how smart you are, how much money you have, or weather or not you're imprisoned. But he wants us to follow his example. Jesus explained this in Matthew, by parable. If we do not forgive what we think is unforgivable, God will not forgive us. This message is littered all thoughout the Bible, both old, and new testament. Most Christans, like 99%, only ever open their Bible in church, otherwise it's a paper weight, and sadly most churches don't emphasize the truly important message. Our problems with our parents are meant to represent our problems with God, this is why we all have them. Once we show the willingness to forgive their inadequacy, God pays closer attention to us. Before this step you're not saved, no matter how many times you go to church. This is why God stays at arm's length. Once you put in the inner work, showing this mustard seed of Faith, God rushes into your life in a very real way. comment:
This is actually a very big issue. How do we define abuse? 

I think one of the major difficulties is defining exactly where you want to draw that line. If I we are talking about physical assault, then I would bet that most men have been physically assaulted by a woman they were involved with. 

Speaking from my own experience, all but one of my girlfriends physically assaulted me at some point. I have been punched, kicked, bitten, even head butted. 

But would I call that abuse? Is someone hitting you or biting you abuse? I fought grown men in cages. When girlfriends would punch me or bite me or claw me, I just laughed. It‚Äôs hard to take it seriously as a threat. I could‚Äôve knocked them out with one punch if I wanted to, so it‚Äôs not like I was in fear of them.

And I think that‚Äôs actually the problem. Because I didn‚Äôt feel threatened or feel fear, I did nothing about it. I didn‚Äôt think of it as abuse. I didn‚Äôt even think it was wrong. 

As men we are taught not to hit women. It would be wrong to defend yourself. But if another man hit me, even a small weak man who posed no real threat, I would knock his ass out. I would never tolerate that type of behavior from another man. However, men get in trouble if they defend themselves from women.

So, do you have a double standard. Women get a free pass for hitting men, and men can do nothing about it because if they hit back or try to defend themselves, men are guilty of abuse. If a man complains that he was abused, he‚Äôs a joke and people will laugh at him for getting beaten up by his wife. If a man defense himself, then he is an abuser. Men can‚Äôt win. It is a lose lose situation for men.

comment:
Men almost always get the short end of the stick.  Society is set up this way, and most people simply don't care.  If a man pushes back, they just laugh at him and tell him to "man up".
I was a hard worker from an early age, by the time I was 23 I had a house and my own small business.
I met a girl when I was 23, we dated for two years, she acted like a great girlfriend.  She immediately changed when we came home from the wedding.  When I confronted her about that, her reply was "I acted that way during dating otherwise you wouldn't have married me".  So I spent years in a bad married trying to make it work with no effort from her.
When I finally couldn't take any more I told her I wanted a divorce.  We saw marriage counselors and even they asked me why I stayed so long with what she was doing in the marriage.  She refused to change.  So I filed for divorce.
All of our "friends" turned on me, they told her to take me for everything that I had.  Little did I know that the divorce laws in BC do exactly that.
I had to sell my house, I had to buy her a new car, I had to pay all of her debt and credit cards, I had to pay all of her lawyer and legal fees, I had to pay her 10 years of alimony that was 40% of my income before taxes, she got half of my business, she got all of the savings, and I had to pay her utilities for one year.
I had nothing left.  I couldn't even afford rent on what was left over for me.  I was homeless for a year, sleeping in my car or on a friend's couch.  I didn't start to get back onto my feet until I was in my mid 40's and the alimony and everything was over.  I lost everything else I had worked for.
The bottom line is, don't get involved with women.  Don't even live with them.  Where I live in BC you are automatically classified as "common law" after two years of living with a woman, which gives her full property rights as if you were married.  So women just take advantage of that and abuse men and take them for everything they have.  I don't know of even one man who is happily married.  You can thank feminism and white-knight men who make the laws.

comment:
Generally speaking, I agree with you (as I usually do).  However, I believe that you got something wrong on this one.  You rightly pointed out how we don't really know the extent or dynamic of the abuse in their relationship, but then pointed out how it's possible that they were abusive to each other.  It's possibly the way you worded it, but it sounds like the current situation would be acceptable to you if they were both abusers.

If we're going to live in a world where men and women are to be on equal footing, this can't be the case.  They are both abusers (in that scenario), but the man loses his livelihood and has his reputation destroyed and the woman keeps her career AND gets new opportunities?  I would suggest that anyone that thinks that setup is ok where they both did the same wrong thing isn't much better than someone who thinks that this outcome is justified if the woman is the only abuser.

Again, I generally agree with your take on this situation, but I believe that the principle that gets you there should still apply even in cases where they're both abustive.

comment: The thing is that this is something that affects everyone, not just men. It is hard enough for a woman to be believed (I speak from my own experience), but for a man it's damn near impossible. Now looking at this case with Johnny; he has so much evidence of her being an abuser, even her admitting to abusing him. Many survivors are lucky to have even half of the amount of evidence that he does. At the same time there is ZERO evidence that he ever laid a hand on her - and this despite her recording practically their whole relationship (so in other words; he's not just a pirate, he's a ninja as well). So even with all of this evidence, the UK court ruled against him (the judge was clearly biased, but that's another issue that I'm not gonna jump in to here - you can find the connections with a simple search on here or on Google) and he is being further abused by the media. What does this say to other abuse survivors (especially men)? Especially when they don't have the kind of evidence and/or resources that he does? Don't forget that she also has been arrested for DV in the past, while Johnny has not. The fact that she is supposed to represent victims of DV honestly makes me feel sick to my stomach. Watching her constantly getting rewarded, while he is being ostracized breaks my heart. I don't know Johnny, obviously, but after having been through the same thing (albeit on a much smaller scale), his case feels incredibly personal to me as well as other DV survivors that I have spoken to. Every setback for him is a slap in the face of all real victims of DV, and so is every reward towards her.

comment:
You missed the point which makes this all the more worse. The case was never a domestic violence case, it had nothing to do with domestic violence. It was a libel case. The accusation the Sun made was libellous and contemptuous, regardless if their source was directly involved in the accusation as an alleged victim the matter had not been to criminal court and if any criminal proceedings were indeed pending it is unlawful for details of the case to be published, including allegations unrelated to actual charges being laid which have never been. A journalist in the UK can say Bob is an alleged car thief if Bob has actually been charged by police with auto theft, stipulating use of the term alleged to prevent libel, however it is libellous and contemptuous to publish that Bob is a car thief where Bob has never been charged with auto theft, even if the journalist's aunt May swears she read it in some tea leaves. It's also contemptuous to discuss any details of Bob's alleged car thieving whilst any court proceedings maybe pending on the matter. In other words it has to be accusations of which he's been criminally charged and they have to stipulate alleged unless it's been to court, in which case they can only say what the court ruled. Otherwise: breaking the law, no journalist exemption on that one.

Now this is all the case has ever been about, Johnny Depp has never been prosecuted for spousal abuse in the UK and this fact alone should've had the Sun held in contempt by a British court for making criminal accusations with neither a court ruling to validate them nor existing criminal charges to allege them. There is no reason to hear any evidence supporting what are, by definition, at the time hollow claims of a criminal nature. It is unlawful by and of itself and that should've been the end of the matter. Sun editorial proprietary and specific journalist punitively fined, conviction recorded, Depp gets the satisfaction of seeing justice done.

But this would've been small fry by American conventions, where libel is a civil lawsuit involving not perhaps a hundred thousand dollars but a hundred million dollars in combined punitive and damages claims and Depp was obviously trying this route using the British court system, which just isn't the way magistrates in the UK think at all. So what they did was turn it into a circus and an actual spousal abuse hearing within a civil proceedings. Not only did this derail completely from the original libel case, destroying it from the very beginning but it also lowered the necessary jurisprudence in criminal cases from a 95% surety of an evidentiary basis to a 51% popular ruling on a jury basis. Depp was a brainless moron to go along with this, he had absolutely no chance simply on the basis of being old and creepy looking whilst Amber's still a hot young blonde, which is all the lawfully required evidence a civil case needs for a ruling, that's why there's completely different rules in criminal cases (which even so can turn into a popularity contest by at least some degree).

Whilst it's a bit of Darwinism for a major celebrity to have it turn out this way for him by pretentiously agreeing to such a thing instead of leaving it at a UK style defamation lawsuit or making false claims criminal proceedings with probably a 15K damages claim instead of probably 150 million he would've wanted and been more used to in America; nevertheless it is still a recklessly irresponsible thing for the UK court system to have done and shows them to be the same dangerously Woke collectivist cuntbags that've been taking over the west's institutions with a nefarious socialist totalitarianism. They were perfectly happy to provide all the rope Depp needed to hang himself. What they should've done is said no, we don't do things that way in the UK court system Mr Depp, you won't be getting a giant damages claim from the Sun but they will be given punitive measures by the court (mainly the lead journo cops a conviction and/or hefty fine). There would've been no need to prove or disprove the Sun's criminal allegations, it was unlawful to make them in the first place if he just went about it using the UK system instead of trying to apply the American one, but onus is really on the court to have put their foot down on this. They turned themselves into a circus and that's the disturbing thing about it all.

And to put that more simply the court should've prohibited the Sun from attempting to validate their libellous accusations. It was unlawful to make them and that is all the court should've heard to rule upon. So literally, what happened was an out and out circus. That's terrifying for the general public of their court system.

comment:
Hey Sydney. I hope you read and respond to this, but if not, it‚Äôs alright.

If I‚Äôm being completely honest, the world needs not just more women like you, but PEOPLE like you, in it. The way society is being run nowadays makes it seem like the Gestapo have been rebranded as some kind of Identity Police where if you‚Äôre male, you‚Äôre automatically a target because ‚ÄúmUh pAtRiArChY REEEEEEEEE!‚Äù

Personal story: In college, I was with a woman 5 years older than me that used me for my body. We were in a relationship for nine months, and we‚Äôd been intimate several times, most of which I didn‚Äôt really want to since I prefer to get to know someone over (I guess what society would call) a long time, maybe a year or two. We‚Äôd gone to the same school, and we seemed to have a lot in common, so our relationship started out great. We were flirty, but it never really went anywhere at first. I had made a promise to my parents a while before I started college that I would wait to finish school until I started becoming sexually active, but I guess she must‚Äôve gotten annoyed by that and told me in July of 2015 that if I didn‚Äôt have sex with her, she‚Äôd break up with me. The only reason I went through with it is because I didn‚Äôt think I would find anyone else like her and I was afraid to lose her. I found out things about later down the line that she had a reputation for being promiscuous with multiple men before me, so I gave her the choice to end the relationship. Her friends proceeded to trash me on social media and the last thing she said to me before we broke up was ‚Äújust let it happen‚Äù as she tried to perform oral sex on me. I felt horrible after that relationship ended, and it showed me that women can be just as abusive as men, however more mental and psychological than physical. I‚Äôd like to thank you for being the voice I was too afraid to let out during that time in my life. Women definitely need to be held more accountable for their actions, and the Depp/Heard case is a prime example of why things like patriarchy don‚Äôt exist, and that our society favors women, contradictory to most that argue otherwise.

You are amazing. Please keep fighting the good fight for the men who are victims and for the people who actually have gone through abuse. Ever since I found your channel, I‚Äôve supported you and your videos. I‚Äôm not going to stop, either.
